Divyansh Mehta
25BCY10194
Branch: CSE (Cyber Security & Digital Forensics)
University: VIT Bhopal
Course: CSE0001 Digital Literacy


This project was undertaken as part of the Digital Literacy course with the objective of developing essential digital skills required in today’s academic and professional environment. As a Student Digital Ambassador, the goal was to understand and demonstrate various aspects of digital literacy including online presence, safe communication, and awareness of cyber threats.

The project consists of five tasks covering infographic creation, digital portfolio setup, platform exploration, email etiquette, and cybercrime awareness. Each task helped in building practical knowledge and improving digital responsibility.

In Task 1, I created a digital literacy awareness infographic using Canva. The infographic covered key topics such as the meaning of digital literacy, safe internet practices, and proper email etiquette. The aim was to present important information in a visually appealing and easy-to-understand format.

While designing, I focused on keeping the layout clean and minimal, using icons and short bullet points for clarity. One challenge I faced was balancing the amount of information with design simplicity. However, the process was interesting as it helped me understand how visual communication can make complex topics more accessible.

In Task 2, I created and updated my profiles on GitHub, LinkedIn, and Kaggle to build a professional digital presence. GitHub is used for hosting and managing projects, LinkedIn helps in professional networking, and Kaggle is useful for data science and learning through practice.

This task helped me understand the importance of maintaining a clean and professional online identity. Over the next four years, I plan to regularly update my profiles with new skills, projects, and achievements. This will help me in internships and career opportunities.

In Task 3, I explored coding and collaboration platforms. I used HackerRank to solve a beginner-level problem, which helped me understand basic problem-solving in programming. Additionally, I created a Google Form as a digital literacy quiz, which included both multiple-choice and short-answer questions.

This task demonstrated how online platforms can be used for both learning and collaboration. The coding platform helped me practice logical thinking, while Google Forms showed how data can be collected and analyzed efficiently. These tools will be useful in my academic journey.

In Task 4, I learned about professional communication through email writing and social media etiquette. I drafted two formal emails, one to a professor and another for an internship opportunity, ensuring proper structure and tone.

A situation where poor communication can cause problems is when a student sends an informal or unclear email to a professor, which may lead to misunderstandings or being ignored. This task helped me understand the importance of clarity, politeness, and professionalism in digital communication.

In Task 5, I studied phishing as a form of cybercrime and created a case study along with a prevention checklist. I was surprised by how easily people can be tricked into sharing sensitive information through fake messages and websites.

This task made me more aware of online risks, and I have decided to be more cautious while clicking links and sharing information. I will also ensure that I verify sources before trusting any digital communication.

Overall, this project provided valuable insights into digital literacy and its importance in daily life. It helped me build a strong foundation in using digital tools responsibly, communicating professionally, and staying safe online. These skills will be beneficial throughout my academic journey and future career.


